<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Submission to Select Committee</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">AFS0026</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">evidence submitted by</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> Future</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">Our response focuses on</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">- </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">The functions and responsibilities in relation to academies and free schools of local authorities and other </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">organisations operating between the Secretary of State and individual schools; what these functions and responsibilities should be; and what gaps there are in support for schools at this level</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.39pt; padding-left:4.61pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">Comprehensive Future’s aim is a comprehensive secondary schoo</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">l system with fair admissions to all publicly funded schools and an end to selection by ability and aptitude. The campaign is non party political and open to all.  We campaign by lobbying Government, providing evidence, informing the media and supporting l</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">ocal campaigns on admissions. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.94pt; padding-left:3.06pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">Summary</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">Because an increasing number of schools are becoming </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">academies and therefore </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">own admission authorities there is a danger that </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">we are likely to return to the confusion and unfairness of the past</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt"> over school admissions</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">. S</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">ocial segregation between schools is likely to increase.</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">Therefore t</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">here is need for coherence in the monitoring </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">of admissions at national level and extending the local authorities’ responsibility to ensure fairness in admissions</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt"> and appeals to all schools.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">In order to ensure fairness and a more level playing field in relation to admissions l</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">ocal authorities should be given more powers over admissions </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">for all local schools </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">and the support to carry them out.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">Local authorities shoul</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">d compare the intakes of own admission authorities schools with the locality and report on that in their annual reports.</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt"> Data to do this should be available nationally.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">Local authorities should manage admissions for all local schools.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">Local forums consider</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">ing admissions should be reintroduced.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">Banding where parents have to take their children to the school for tests should be discouraged.</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt"> If banding is to be used, it should be carried out for all children by the local authority.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">Appeals should be done for a</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">ll schools by the local authority.</span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.86pt; padding-left:3.14pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">A</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">s more schools become academies ie own admission authority schools able to set their own admission criteria, decide which applicant meets them and carry out appeals we are likely to return to the confusion and unfairne</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">ss of the past. The creation of a parallel school system outside the (already fragmented) maintained school sector has led to confusion and unfairness in admissions eg only academies are able to prioritise applicants eligible for free school meals and the </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">Secretary of State is able to allow academies not to comply with the School Admissions Code. </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">Where there are </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">many admission authorities in a local authority using different criteria some children could be left without a school which they can reasonably acc</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">ess.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><a href="http://www.education.gov.uk/schoolsadjudicator/about/a00199754/annual-report-of-the-chief-schools-adjudicator-for-england"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">The OSA Annual Report</span></a><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt"> calls on the DfE to ensure that there is clear guidance for new schools and those that change their status to become their own admission authority as they seem unaware of the mandatory requirements of consultation, determination and publication of admissi</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">on arrangements</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.57pt; padding-left:3.43pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">The 2013  </span><a href="http://www.education.gov.uk/schoolsadjudicator/about/a00199754/annual-report-of-the-chief-schools-adjudicator-for-england"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Annual report of Chief Schools Adjudicator</span></a><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt"> reported that over 7,562 schools were own admission authorities an increase of roughly a 1000 from the previous year.  This is likely to increase, at least at secondary level.  As Coldron, West and Allen noted in 2010 </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Previous studies (West et al., 2004; </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">West et al., 2011) have shown that schools that are their own admission authority are more likely to have admissions criteria that enable schools to be unfairly selective in their intakes and there is therefore a case for moving admission powers away from </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">individual schools and putting them into the hands of an independent body that administers admissions across an area and ideally sets admissions criteria that are consistent across all schools. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.03pt; padding-left:2.97pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">Reflecting concern about schools having intakes which differ</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt"> greatly from their neighbourhood the </span><a href="http://www.thersa.org/action-research-centre/learning,-cognition-and-creativity/education/policy-and-research/academies-commission"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">RSA Pearson Commission on Academies</span></a><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt"> proposed that schools should compar</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">e their intakes to those applying</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt"> to see if they are admitting a broad range reflective of the local community.  Comprehensive Future has said instead </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">that it would be more effective if this were done by local authorities comparing the intakes of their loc</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">al schools with the locality, as comparing applicants with intake does not take into account that some parents may be put off applying to a particular school</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">in </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">the first place</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">. Local authorities are required by the Code to make annual reports about local </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">admissions, so this duty could be added to these reporting requirements.</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">There should be data nationally available which would enable </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">these </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">comparisons between the intakes of all schools and their communities, this would support local authorities to ensure</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt"> fair admissions and allow them to provide this information locally.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.26pt; padding-left:3.74pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">School Admissions </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">Code allows three types of banding- across the range of applicants to the school; across the range of ability of children in the local area and the national ability</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt"> range. Several </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">academies </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">band by setting a test of applicants to the school which can mean that only those children whose families are able to arrange to bring them can sit </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">the test. This naturally excludes some families.  A few local authorities set a te</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">st for all children. If banding is to be introduced </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">omprehensive Future believes it should be for all schools in the area and that the test should take place in the primary schools.  However there are concerns over banding. Like all forms of selection it </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">can separate friends. In rural areas it could mean children travelling long distances to schools.  Mortimore has pointed out that like all forms of selection it is based on perceived ability and is too unreliable and leads to low expectations of those so l</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">abelled. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.39pt; padding-left:2.61pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">Some years ago the Code gave the local authority a major role in coordinating admissions ending the situation where parents had to apply to several schools individually. This made a huge difference to parents’ experience of choosing a school. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.03pt; padding-left:2.97pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">Local authorities should be supported as the middle tier in between schools and national Government.  They have democratic legitimacy and local accessibility. They have a crucial role to play in ensuring fair admissions. They are ideally placed to support </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">parents and children locally. All local authorities should reach the level of the best, including fulfilling their responsibility in ensuring fair school admissions. They should be encouraged and funded in order to carry out their existing duty to ensure f</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">air access, ensuring that they challenge all local schools to have lawful admission arrangements and provide clear information for parents.  The 2013 report of the </span><a href="http://www.education.gov.uk/schoolsadjudicator/about/a00199754/annual-report-of-the-chief-schools-adjudicator-for-england"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Chief S</span><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">c</span><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">hools Adjudicator</span></a><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt"> indicates that some local authorities </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">are failing to </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">challenge local own admission authorities to meet the requirements of the code.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#231f20; font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">The local authorities’ role should be strengthened by giving them a new statutory duty to manage school admissions in all local schools by making the decision about whether applicants meet the admissions criteria. This would ease the burden on schools and </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">make the process more open.  The </span><a href="http://www.ippr.org/publication/55/1582/school-admissionsfair-choice-for-parents-and-pupils"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">IPPR in 2007</span></a><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">  in research on admissions went to recommend that to ensure fairness and a balanced intake all admissi</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">on criteria should be set by the local authority and managed by the local authority.</span><span style="color:#231f20; font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> We think that local authorities should perform the role of allocating places and that there should be appropriate safeguards and a means of appeal for schools and parents</span><span style="color:#231f20; font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="color:#231f20; font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">Coldron, West and Allen (2010) commenting on the need for external administration of admissions said  </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">if admissions were administered by an independent body, it would increase the transparency of the admissions process and ensure that decisions are not ma</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">de behind closed doors with no external scrutiny. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#231f20; font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="color:#231f20; font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">Previous codes required local authorities to set up admissions forums involving all local schools looking at the fairness of local admissions but the Coalition removed the requirement, and now claims thi</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">s as part of its policy of removing a burden on schools. Comprehensive Future </span><a href="http://comprehensivefuture.org.uk/survey-on-admissions-forums-summary-of-findings/"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">surveyed</span></a><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt"> the views of Chairs of Admission Forums in 2011</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt"> We found strong suppo</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">rt for such a local forum. </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">The removal of the statutory duty to have admission forums has meant that a valuable means of involving local stakeholders </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">(including academies) </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">in considering the fairness of local admissions has been lost. It may be that ther</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">e could be some streamlining of local forums involving local stakeholders in education but the duty to provide a local forum to consider school admissions should be reinstated and supported, they should agree the admission criteria for all local schools. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">As well as deciding on who to admit own admission authority schools also carry out their own appeals. The recent </span><a href="http://www.thersa.org/action-research-centre/learning,-cognition-and-creativity/education/reports-and-events/reports/unleashing-greatness"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">RSA Commission on academies</span></a><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt"> concluded that local authorities should carry out the appeals on all their schools and this was supported by the then Administrative, Justice and Tribunals Council.   This would lift the burden from schools and ensur</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">e consistency of approach.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">There is a need for a national monitoring of admission and appeals.  </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">However b</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">ecause of the fragmented nature of the education system monitoring at national level is complex. Although objections about the admission arrangements of academies can now be made to the adjudicator the Education Funding Agency has a role in ensuring compli</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">ance with the funding agreement which will include admission arrangements and over the </span><a href="http://www.education.gov.uk/schools/adminandfinance/schooladmissions/a00204768/appeals"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">administration of appeals</span></a><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">.  The role to investigate maladministration of maintained school appeals is with the </span><a href="http://www.lgo.org.uk/publications/fact-sheets/complaints-about-school-admissions/"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Local Government Ombudsman</span></a><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">Changes in the current Code allow academi</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">es to agree a variation in relation to admission arrangements with the Secretary of State and no objection to the Adjudicator can be made about that. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">Although the adjudicator can make recommendations having investigated which may go beyond the original o</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">bjection action can only be taken if there is an objection. This illustrates the need for </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">energetic </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">local monitoring. </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">There is a case for </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">the monitoring and </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">regulation of admissions and appeals to be the same for all schools, academies or maintained.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">References</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">Allen, West and Coldron </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">(2010) </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">DFE Research Report, RR038 </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">Brooks,R and Tough, S (2007)  School Admissions: Fair choice for parents and pupils, </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">Comprehensive Future (2011) Survey on Admissions Forums – summary of findings</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">DfE (2012) School Ad</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">missions Code</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">Gorard S, (2013) Narrowing Down 